{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612787"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16287"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16287"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.87,0,0.03,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8978"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7493"},{"type":"tags","id":"7495"},{"type":"tags","id":"7496"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"},{"type":"tags","id":"10438"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inner ear is a complex structure located within the temporal bone that contains specialised sensory organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the contents of the inner ear?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contains receptors for both hearing and balance","Contains only balance receptors","Air-filled cavity surrounded by bone","Contains only hearing receptors","Fluid-filled space without sensory receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inner ear \u003Cstrong\u003Econtains receptors for both hearing and balance\u003C/strong\u003E. It consists of the bony and membranous labyrinths, which are fluid-filled structures. The cochlea houses the organ of Corti for hearing, while the vestibular apparatus (semicircular canals, utricle, and saccule) contains receptors for balance and spatial orientation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option stating the inner ear \u003Cstrong\u003Econtains only balance receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the inner ear contains receptors for both hearing and balance, not just balance. Similarly, the option suggesting it \u003Cstrong\u003Econtains only hearing receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the inner ear contains both hearing and balance receptors, not just hearing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe description of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eair-filled cavity surrounded by bone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the inner ear is filled with fluid (endolymph and perilymph), not air. The middle ear is the air-filled cavity. The option describing a \u003Cstrong\u003Efluid-filled space without sensory receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect because while the inner ear is fluid-filled, it contains specialised sensory receptors for both hearing and balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The inner ear contains fluid-filled membranous and bony labyrinths that house receptors for both hearing and balance.","The cochlea contains the organ of Corti for hearing, while the vestibular apparatus contains receptors for balance and spatial orientation.","The inner ear is filled with endolymph and perilymph fluids, not air."],"references":["Heine PA. Anatomy of the ear. Vet Clin North Am Small Anim Pract. 2004 Mar;34(2):379-95. doi: 10.1016/j.cvsm.2003.10.003. PMID: 15062614.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16287"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97939"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T15:48:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T15:50:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8978"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115940"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd